M_LOC[   1] = "Long Discourses 1";
M_LOC[   2] = "The Prime Net";
M_LOC[   3] = "1. Talk on Wanderers";
M_LOC[   4] = "So I have heard.";
M_LOC[   5] = "At one time the Buddha was traveling along the road between Rājagaha and Nālanda together with a large Saṅgha of around five hundred mendicants.";
M_LOC[   6] = "The wanderer Suppiya was also traveling along the same road, together with his pupil, the brahmin student Brahmadatta.";
M_LOC[   7] = "Meanwhile, Suppiya criticized the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha in many ways,";
M_LOC[   8] = "but his pupil Brahmadatta praised them in many ways.";
M_LOC[   9] = "And so both teacher and pupil followed behind the Buddha and the Saṅgha of mendicants directly contradicting each other.";
M_LOC[  10] = "Then the Buddha took up residence for the night in the royal rest-house in Ambalaṭṭhikā together with the Saṅgha of mendicants.";
M_LOC[  11] = "And Suppiya and Brahmadatta did likewise.";
M_LOC[  12] = "There too, Suppiya criticized the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha in many ways,";
M_LOC[  13] = "but his pupil Brahmadatta praised them in many ways.";
M_LOC[  14] = "And so both teacher and pupil kept on directly contradicting each other.";
M_LOC[  15] = "Then several mendicants rose at the crack of dawn and sat together in the pavilion, where the topic of evaluation came up:";
M_LOC[  16] = "“It’s incredible, reverends, it’s amazing how the diverse attitudes of sentient beings have been clearly comprehended by the Blessed One, who knows and sees, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha.";
M_LOC[  17] = "For this Suppiya criticizes the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha in many ways,";
M_LOC[  18] = "while his pupil Brahmadatta praises them in many ways.";
M_LOC[  19] = "And so both teacher and pupil followed behind the Buddha and the Saṅgha of mendicants directly contradicting each other.”";
M_LOC[  20] = "When the Buddha found out about this discussion on evaluation among the mendicants, he went to the pavilion, where he sat on the seat spread out and addressed the mendicants,";
M_LOC[  21] = "“Mendicants, what were you sitting talking about just now? What conversation was left unfinished?”";
M_LOC[  22] = "The mendicants told him what had happened, adding,";
M_LOC[  23] = "“This was our conversation that was unfinished when the Buddha arrived.”";
M_LOC[  24] = "“Mendicants, if others criticize me, the teaching, or the Saṅgha, don’t make yourselves resentful, bitter, and exasperated.";
M_LOC[  25] = "You’ll get angry and upset, which would be an obstacle for you alone.";
M_LOC[  26] = "If others were to criticize me, the teaching, or the Saṅgha, and you got angry and upset, would you be able to understand whether they spoke well or poorly?”";
M_LOC[  27] = "“No, sir.”";
M_LOC[  28] = "“If others criticize me, the teaching, or the Saṅgha, you should explain that what is untrue is in fact untrue:";
M_LOC[  29] = "‘This is why that’s untrue, this is why that’s false. There’s no such thing in us, it’s not found among us.’";
M_LOC[  30] = "If others praise me, the teaching, or the Saṅgha, don’t make yourselves thrilled, elated, and excited.";
M_LOC[  31] = "You’ll get thrilled, elated, and excited, which would be an obstacle for you alone.";
M_LOC[  32] = "If others praise me, the teaching, or the Saṅgha, you should acknowledge that what is true is in fact true:";
M_LOC[  33] = "‘This is why that’s true, this is why that’s correct. There is such a thing in us, it is found among us.’";
M_LOC[  34] = "2. Ethics";
M_LOC[  35] = "2.1. The Shorter Section on Ethics";
M_LOC[  36] = "When an ordinary person speaks praise of the Realized One, they speak only of trivial, insignificant details of mere ethics.";
M_LOC[  37] = "And what are the trivial, insignificant details of mere ethics that an ordinary person speaks of?";
M_LOC[  38] = "‘The ascetic Gotama has given up killing living creatures. He has renounced the rod and the sword. He’s scrupulous and kind, living full of compassion for all living beings.’";
M_LOC[  39] = "Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.";
M_LOC[  40] = "The shorter section on ethics is finished.";
M_LOC[  41] = "2.2. The Middle Section on Ethics";
M_LOC[  42] = "‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in injuring plants and seeds.";
M_LOC[  43] = "‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in storing up goods for their own use.<br>This includes such things as food, drink, clothes, vehicles, bedding, fragrance, and material possessions.<br>The ascetic Gotama refrains from storing up such goods.’<br>Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.";
M_LOC[  44] = "‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in seeing shows.<br>This includes such things as dancing, singing, music, performances, and storytelling; clapping, gongs, and kettle-drums; art exhibitions and acrobatic displays; battles of elephants, horses, buffaloes, bulls, goats, rams, chickens, and quails; staff-fights, boxing, and wrestling; combat, roll calls of the armed forces, battle-formations, and regimental reviews.<br>The ascetic Gotama refrains from such shows.’<br>Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.";
M_LOC[  45] = "‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in gambling that causes negligence.";
M_LOC[  46] = "This includes such things as checkers, draughts, checkers in the air, hopscotch, spillikins, board-games, tip-cat, drawing straws, dice, leaf-flutes, toy plows, somersaults, pinwheels, toy measures, toy carts, toy bows, guessing words from syllables, and guessing another’s thoughts.";
M_LOC[  47] = "The ascetic Gotama refrains from such gambling.’";
M_LOC[  48] = "‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in unworthy talk. This includes such topics as";
M_LOC[  49] = "talk about kings, bandits, and ministers; talk about armies, threats, and wars; talk about food, drink, clothes, and beds; talk about garlands and fragrances; talk about family, vehicles, villages, towns, cities, and countries; talk about women and heroes; street talk and well talk; talk about the departed; motley talk; tales of land and sea; and talk about being reborn in this or that state of existence.";
M_LOC[  50] = "The ascetic Gotama refrains from such unworthy talk.’";
M_LOC[  51] = "Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.";
M_LOC[  52] = "The middle section on ethics is finished.";
M_LOC[  53] = "2.3. The Large Section on Ethics";
M_LOC[  54] = "‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood.";
M_LOC[  55] = "This includes such fields as limb-reading, omenology, divining celestial portents, interpreting dreams, divining bodily marks, divining holes in cloth gnawed by mice, fire offerings, ladle offerings, offerings of husks, rice powder, rice, ghee, or oil; offerings from the mouth, blood sacrifices, palmistry; geomancy for building sites, fields, and cemeteries; exorcisms, earth magic, snake charming, poisons; the crafts of the scorpion, the rat, the bird, and the crow; prophesying life span, chanting for protection, and animal cries.";
M_LOC[  56] = "The ascetic Gotama refrains from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood.’";
M_LOC[  57] = "Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.";
M_LOC[  58] = "‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood.";
M_LOC[  59] = "This includes reading the marks of gems, cloth, clubs, swords, spears, arrows, weapons, women, men, boys, girls, male and female bondservants, elephants, horses, buffaloes, bulls, cows, goats, rams, chickens, quails, monitor lizards, rabbits, tortoises, or deer.";
M_LOC[  60] = "The ascetic Gotama refrains from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood.’";
M_LOC[  61] = "These are the trivial, insignificant details of mere ethics that an ordinary person speaks of when they speak praise of the Realized One.";
M_LOC[  62] = "The longer section on ethics is finished.";
M_LOC[  63] = "3. Views";
M_LOC[  64] = "There are other principles—deep, hard to see, hard to understand, peaceful, sublime, beyond the scope of reason, subtle, comprehensible to the astute—which the Realized One makes known after realizing them with his own insight. Those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.";
M_LOC[  65] = "And what are these principles?";
M_LOC[  66] = "There are some ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the past, and assert various hypotheses concerning the past on eighteen grounds.";
M_LOC[  67] = "There are some ascetics and brahmins who are eternalists, who assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal on four grounds.";
M_LOC[  68] = "And what are the four grounds on which they rely?";
M_LOC[  69] = "It’s when some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect their many kinds of past lives.";
M_LOC[  70] = "That is: one, two, three, four, five, ten, twenty, thirty, forty, fifty, a hundred, a thousand, a hundred thousand rebirths; many eons of the cosmos contracting, many eons of the cosmos expanding, many eons of the cosmos contracting and expanding. They remember: ‘There, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn somewhere else. There, too, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn here.’ And so they recollect their many kinds of past lives, with features and details.";
M_LOC[  71] = "They say:";
M_LOC[  72] = "‘The self and the cosmos are eternal, barren, steady as a mountain peak, standing firm like a pillar.";
M_LOC[  73] = "They remain the same for all eternity, while these sentient beings wander and transmigrate and pass away and rearise.";
M_LOC[  74] = "And what is the fourth ground on which they rely?<br>It’s when some ascetic or brahmin relies on logic and inquiry. They speak of what they have worked out by logic, following a line of inquiry, expressing their own perspective:<br>‘The self and the cosmos are eternal, barren, steady as a mountain peak, standing firm like a pillar.<br>They remain the same for all eternity, while these sentient beings wander and transmigrate and pass away and rearise.’<br>This is the fourth ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal.";
M_LOC[  75] = "These are the four grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal.<br>Any ascetics and brahmins who assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal do so on one or other of these four grounds. Outside of this there is none.<br>The Realized One understands this:";
M_LOC[  76] = "‘If you hold on to and attach to these grounds for views it leads to such and such a destiny in the next life.’";
M_LOC[  77] = "He understands this, and what goes beyond this. Yet since he does not misapprehend that understanding, he has realized extinguishment within himself.";
M_LOC[  78] = "Having truly understood the origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape from feelings, the Realized One is freed through not grasping.";
M_LOC[  79] = "These are the principles—deep, hard to see, hard to understand, peaceful, sublime, beyond the scope of reason, subtle, comprehensible to the astute—which the Realized One makes known after realizing them with his own insight. And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.";
M_LOC[  80] = "3.1.2. Partial Eternalism";
M_LOC[  81] = "There comes a time when, after a very long period has passed, this cosmos contracts.<br>As the cosmos contracts, sentient beings are mostly headed for the realm of streaming radiance.<br>There they are mind-made, feeding on rapture, self-luminous, moving through the sky, steadily glorious, and they remain like that for a very long time.";
M_LOC[  82] = "There comes a time when, after a very long period has passed, this cosmos expands.<br>As it expands an empty mansion of Brahmā appears.<br>Then a certain sentient being—due to the running out of their life-span or merit—passes away from that host of radiant deities and is reborn in that empty mansion of Brahmā.<br>There they are mind-made, feeding on rapture, self-luminous, moving through the sky, steadily glorious, and they remain like that for a very long time.<br>But after staying there all alone for a long time, they become dissatisfied and anxious:<br>‘Oh, if only another being would come to this state of existence.’";
M_LOC[  83] = "Then other sentient beings—due to the running out of their life-span or merit—pass away from that host of radiant deities and are reborn in that empty mansion of Brahmā in company with that being.";
M_LOC[  84] = "There they too are mind-made, feeding on rapture, self-luminous, moving through the sky, steadily glorious, and they remain like that for a very long time.";
M_LOC[  85] = "Now, the being who was reborn there first thinks:";
M_LOC[  86] = "And the being who was reborn first is more long-lived, beautiful, and illustrious than those who arrived later.";
M_LOC[  87] = "It’s possible that one of those beings passes away from that host and is reborn in this state of existence.";
M_LOC[  88] = "Having done so, they go forth from the lay life to homelessness.";
M_LOC[  89] = "By dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus, they experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect that past life, but no further.";
M_LOC[  90] = "They say:";
M_LOC[  91] = "‘He who is Brahmā—the Great Brahmā, the Undefeated, the Champion, the Universal Seer, the Wielder of Power, the Lord God, the Maker, the Author, the Best, the Begetter, the Controller, the Father of those who have been born and those yet to be born—is permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, remaining the same for all eternity.";
M_LOC[  92] = "And what is the third ground on which they rely?";
M_LOC[  93] = "There are gods named ‘malevolent’. They spend too much time gazing at each other, so they grow angry with each other, and their bodies and minds get tired. They pass away from that host of gods.";
M_LOC[  94] = "It’s possible that one of those beings passes away from that host and is reborn in this state of existence.";
M_LOC[  95] = "And what is the fourth ground on which they rely?<br>It’s when some ascetic or brahmin relies on logic and inquiry. They speak of what they have worked out by logic, following a line of inquiry, expressing their own perspective:<br>‘That which is called “the eye” or “the ear” or “the nose” or “the tongue” or “the body”: that self is impermanent, not lasting, transient, perishable.<br>That which is called “mind” or “sentience” or “consciousness”: that self is permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, remaining the same for all eternity.’<br>This is the fourth ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos are partially eternal.<br>These are the four grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins assert that the self and the cosmos are partially eternal and partially not eternal.";
M_LOC[  96] = "Any ascetics and brahmins who assert that the self and the cosmos are partially eternal and partially not eternal do so on one or other of these four grounds. Outside of this there is none.";
M_LOC[  97] = "The Realized One understands this:";
M_LOC[  98] = "‘If you hold on to and attach to these grounds for views it leads to such and such a destiny in the next life.’";
M_LOC[  99] = "He understands this, and what goes beyond this. Yet since he does not misapprehend that understanding, he has realized extinguishment within himself.";
M_LOC[ 100] = "There are some ascetics and brahmins who theorize about size, and assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite on four grounds.";
M_LOC[ 101] = "And what are the four grounds on which they rely?";
M_LOC[ 102] = "It’s when some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they meditate perceiving the cosmos as finite.";
M_LOC[ 103] = "And what is the second ground on which they rely?<br>It’s when some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they meditate perceiving the cosmos as infinite.<br>They say:";
M_LOC[ 104] = "‘The cosmos is infinite and unbounded.";
M_LOC[ 105] = "And what is the third ground on which they rely?<br>It’s when some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they meditate perceiving the cosmos as finite vertically but infinite horizontally.<br>They say:";
M_LOC[ 106] = "‘The cosmos is both finite and infinite.";
M_LOC[ 107] = "And what is the fourth ground on which they rely?<br>It’s when some ascetic or brahmin relies on logic and inquiry. They speak of what they have worked out by logic, following a line of inquiry, expressing their own perspective:<br>‘The cosmos is neither finite nor infinite.<br>The ascetics and brahmins who say that<br>the cosmos is finite are wrong,<br>as are those who say that<br>the cosmos is infinite,<br>and also those who say that<br>the cosmos is both finite and infinite.<br>The cosmos is neither finite nor infinite.’<br>This is the fourth ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite.";
M_LOC[ 108] = "These are the four grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite.";
M_LOC[ 109] = "Any ascetics and brahmins who assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite do so on one or other of these four grounds. Outside of this there is none.";
M_LOC[ 110] = "The Realized One understands this:";
M_LOC[ 111] = "‘If you hold on to and attach to these grounds for views it leads to such and such a destiny in the next life.’";
M_LOC[ 112] = "There are some ascetics and brahmins who are equivocators. Whenever they’re asked a question, they resort to evasiveness and equivocation on four grounds.<br>And what are the four grounds on which they rely?<br>It’s when some ascetic or brahmin doesn’t truly understand what is skillful and what is unskillful.<br>They think:<br>‘I don’t truly understand what is skillful and what is unskillful.<br>If I were to declare that something was skillful or unskillful I might be wrong.";
M_LOC[ 113] = "That would be stressful for me,";
M_LOC[ 114] = "and that stress would be an obstacle.’";
M_LOC[ 115] = "So from fear and disgust with false speech they avoid stating whether something is skillful or unskillful. Whenever they’re asked a question, they resort to evasiveness and equivocation:";
M_LOC[ 116] = "And what is the fourth ground on which they rely?";
M_LOC[ 117] = "It’s when some ascetic or brahmin is dull and stupid.";
M_LOC[ 118] = "Because of that, whenever they’re asked a question, they resort to evasiveness and equivocation:";
M_LOC[ 119] = "There are some ascetics and brahmins who theorize about chance. They assert that the self and the cosmos arose by chance on two grounds.<br>And what are the two grounds on which they rely?";
M_LOC[ 120] = "There are gods named ‘non-percipient beings’.<br>When perception arises they pass away from that host of gods.<br>It’s possible that one of those beings passes away from that host and is reborn in this state of existence.<br>Having done so, they go forth from the lay life to homelessness.<br>By dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus, they experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect the arising of perception, but no further.<br>They say:<br>‘The self and the cosmos arose by chance.<br>Why is that?<br>Because formerly I didn’t exist. Now, having not been, I’ve sprung into existence.’<br>This is the first ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos arose by chance.<br>And what is the second ground on which they rely?<br>It’s when some ascetic or brahmin relies on logic and inquiry.<br>They speak of what they have worked out by logic, following a line of inquiry, expressing their own perspective:";
M_LOC[ 121] = "‘The self and the cosmos arose by chance.’";
M_LOC[ 122] = "These are the two grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins who theorize about chance assert that the self and the cosmos arose by chance.";
M_LOC[ 123] = "Any ascetics and brahmins who theorize about chance do so on one or other of these two grounds. Outside of this there is none.";
M_LOC[ 124] = "The Realized One understands this …";
M_LOC[ 125] = "And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.";
M_LOC[ 126] = "These are the eighteen grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the past assert various hypotheses concerning the past.";
M_LOC[ 127] = "Any ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the past do so on one or other of these eighteen grounds. Outside of this there is none.";
M_LOC[ 128] = "The Realized One understands this:";
M_LOC[ 129] = "‘If you hold on to and attach to these grounds for views it leads to such and such a destiny in the next life.’";
M_LOC[ 130] = "He understands this, and what goes beyond this. Yet since he does not misapprehend that understanding, he has realized extinguishment within himself.";
M_LOC[ 131] = "Having truly understood the origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape from feelings, the Realized One is freed through not grasping.";
M_LOC[ 132] = "These are the principles—deep, hard to see, hard to understand, peaceful, sublime, beyond the scope of reason, subtle, comprehensible to the astute—which the Realized One makes known after realizing them with his own insight. And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.";
M_LOC[ 133] = "3.2. Theories About the Future";
M_LOC[ 134] = "There are some ascetics and brahmins who say there is life after death, and assert that the self lives on after death in a non-percipient form on eight grounds.";
M_LOC[ 135] = "And what are the eight grounds on which they rely?";
M_LOC[ 136] = "They assert: ‘The self is sound and non-percipient after death, and it is physical …";
M_LOC[ 137] = "non-physical …";
M_LOC[ 138] = "There are some ascetics and brahmins who say there is life after death, and assert that the self lives on after death in a neither percipient nor non-percipient form on eight grounds.";
M_LOC[ 139] = "And what are the eight grounds on which they rely?";
M_LOC[ 140] = "These are the eight grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins assert that the self lives on after death in a neither percipient nor non-percipient form.";
M_LOC[ 141] = "Any ascetics and brahmins who assert that the self lives on after death in a neither percipient nor non-percipient form do so on one or other of these eight grounds. Outside of this there is none.";
M_LOC[ 142] = "There are some ascetics and brahmins who are annihilationists. They assert the annihilation, eradication, and obliteration of an existing being on seven grounds.<br>And what are the seven grounds on which they rely?<br>There are some ascetics and brahmins who have this doctrine and view:";
M_LOC[ 143] = "‘This self is physical, made up of the four primary elements, and produced by mother and father. Since it’s annihilated and destroyed when the body breaks up, and doesn’t exist after death, that’s how this self becomes rightly annihilated.’";
M_LOC[ 144] = "That is how some assert the annihilation of an existing being.";
M_LOC[ 145] = "But someone else says to them:";
M_LOC[ 146] = "‘*That* self of which you speak does exist, I don’t deny it.";
M_LOC[ 147] = "But that’s not how *this* self becomes rightly annihilated.";
M_LOC[ 148] = "There is another self that is divine, physical, sensual, consuming solid food.";
M_LOC[ 149] = "You don’t know or see that.";
M_LOC[ 150] = "But I know it and see it.";
M_LOC[ 151] = "Since this self is annihilated and destroyed when the body breaks up, and doesn’t exist after death, that’s how this self becomes rightly annihilated.’";
M_LOC[ 152] = "There are some ascetics and brahmins who speak of extinguishment in the present life. They assert the ultimate extinguishment of an existing being in the present life on five grounds.<br>And what are the five grounds on which they rely?<br>There are some ascetics and brahmins who have this doctrine and view:";
M_LOC[ 153] = "‘When this self amuses itself, supplied and provided with the five kinds of sensual stimulation, that’s how this self attains ultimate extinguishment in the present life.’";
M_LOC[ 154] = "That is how some assert the extinguishment of an existing being in the present life.";
M_LOC[ 155] = "But someone else says to them:";
M_LOC[ 156] = "‘*That* self of which you speak does exist, I don’t deny it.";
M_LOC[ 157] = "But that’s not how *this* self attains ultimate extinguishment in the present life.";
M_LOC[ 158] = "Why is that?";
M_LOC[ 159] = "These are the forty-four grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the future assert various hypotheses concerning the future.<br>Any ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the future do so on one or other of these forty-four grounds. Outside of this there is none.<br>The Realized One understands this …<br>And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.";
M_LOC[ 160] = "These are the sixty-two grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the past and the future assert various hypotheses concerning the past and the future.";
M_LOC[ 161] = "Any ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the past or the future do so on one or other of these sixty-two grounds. Outside of this there is none.";
M_LOC[ 162] = "The Realized One understands this:";
M_LOC[ 163] = "‘If you hold on to and attach to these grounds for views it leads to such and such a destiny in the next life.’";
M_LOC[ 164] = "He understands this, and what goes beyond this. Yet since he does not misapprehend that understanding, he has realized extinguishment within himself.";
M_LOC[ 165] = "Now, these things are only the feeling of those who do not know or see, the agitation and evasiveness of those under the sway of craving. Namely, when those ascetics and brahmins assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal on four grounds …";
M_LOC[ 166] = "partially eternal on four grounds …";
M_LOC[ 167] = "finite or infinite on four grounds …";
M_LOC[ 168] = "or they resort to equivocation on four grounds …";
M_LOC[ 169] = "or they assert that the self and the cosmos arose by chance on two grounds …";
M_LOC[ 170] = "they theorize about the past on these eighteen grounds …";
M_LOC[ 171] = "or they assert that the self lives on after death in a percipient form on sixteen grounds …";
M_LOC[ 172] = "or that the self lives on after death in a non-percipient form on eight grounds …";
M_LOC[ 173] = "or that the self lives on after death in a neither percipient nor non-percipient form on eight grounds …";
M_LOC[ 174] = "or they assert the annihilation of an existing being on seven grounds …";
M_LOC[ 175] = "or they assert the ultimate extinguishment of an existing being in the present life on five grounds …";
M_LOC[ 176] = "they theorize about the future on these forty-four grounds …";
M_LOC[ 177] = "When those ascetics and brahmins theorize about the past and the future on these sixty-two grounds, these things are only the feeling of those who do not know or see, the agitation and evasiveness of those under the sway of craving.";
M_LOC[ 178] = "4.2. Conditioned by Contact";
M_LOC[ 179] = "Now, these things are conditioned by contact. Namely, when those ascetics and brahmins assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal on four grounds …";
M_LOC[ 180] = "partially eternal on four grounds …";
M_LOC[ 181] = "finite or infinite on four grounds …";
M_LOC[ 182] = "or they resort to equivocation on four grounds …";
M_LOC[ 183] = "or they assert that the self and the cosmos arose by chance on two grounds …";
M_LOC[ 184] = "they theorize about the past on these eighteen grounds …";
M_LOC[ 185] = "or they assert that the self lives on after death in a percipient form on sixteen grounds …";
M_LOC[ 186] = "or that the self lives on after death in a non-percipient form on eight grounds …";
M_LOC[ 187] = "or that the self lives on after death in a neither percipient nor non-percipient form on eight grounds …";
M_LOC[ 188] = "or they assert the annihilation of an existing being on seven grounds …";
M_LOC[ 189] = "or they assert the ultimate extinguishment of an existing being in the present life on five grounds …";
M_LOC[ 190] = "they theorize about the future on these forty-four grounds …";
M_LOC[ 191] = "When those ascetics and brahmins theorize about the past and the future on these sixty-two grounds, that too is conditioned by contact.";
M_LOC[ 192] = "4.3. Not Possible";
M_LOC[ 193] = "";
M_LOC[ 194] = "";
M_LOC[ 195] = "";
M_LOC[ 196] = "";
